Cell[TextData[{
 "As first pointed out by Einstein et al. (1935), entangled quantum states \
have many intriguing properties that are difficult to intuitively understand \
and that raise many questions concerning the foundation of quantum mechanics. \
The non-local property\[LongDash]the very property pointed out by Einstein et \
al. (1935)\[LongDash]is the representative property of entangled states. \
Quantum entanglement also provides a fundamental explanation of ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["quantum decoherence",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumNoiseAndDecoherence"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", the process through which a quantum system loses its quantum effects. In \
quantum computation, quantum information, and quantum communication, \
entanglement is regarded as a valuable resource that enables many amazing \
quantum effects, such quantum supremacy and unconditional security, which are \
impossible in the classical world. One of the most illustrative examples is \
",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["quantum teleportation",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumTeleportation"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->583149690,ExpressionUUID->"8aa0ccb2-f081-4c66-a358-26adabf5ba23"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Mixed States", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section14",
 CellID->2028958569,ExpressionUUID->"76dbdbfd-cb43-4e22-8a95-570dc9c5a710"],

Cell["\<\
One often encounters a situation where the state of a system is not \
completely known. In this case, the system is said to be in a mixed state. A \
common example is when the system is interacting with its surroundings.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->813838470,ExpressionUUID->"92d45023-e5fe-4c37-92c0-1b2e3d9ee31b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A mixed state is a statistical mixture of pure states and is characterized \
in terms of a statistical ensemble, where different state vectors ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "12ef3621-cddf-4a5c-b63b-d1f979fb17ff"],
 " are found with probabilities ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["p", "\[Mu]"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "df5659ea-773c-4cf3-b44f-5e202fa8e161"],
 ". (Here, note that the different pure states ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "eb562a4e-ede2-41ca-b5bd-e4bc7f0b6c88"],
 " in the mixture do not have to be orthogonal to each other, and they do not \
necessarily span the Hilbert space, either.) Such an ensemble is efficiently \
represented by a density operator (which is often just called density matrix \
for historical reasons) constructed as"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1733779645,ExpressionUUID->"73d0adef-e176-49eb-a624-d36810704580"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Rho]", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", "\[Mu]"], 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
       "Ket"], 
      SubscriptBox["p", "\[Mu]"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
       "Bra"]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fb6a6d46-1e33-4a8b-aad5-748d73558ee5"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->859817547,ExpressionUUID->"4745cc8a-b7ce-4e21-9847-deed3f434ae5"],

Cell["\<\
Sometimes, it is convenient to describe the statistical mixture in terms of a \
set of unnormalized vectors\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->536051766,ExpressionUUID->"79229fd2-a074-4671-a28f-b8e8fe747b65"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     TemplateBox[{
       SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]", "\[Prime]"]},
      "Ket"], ":=", 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
       "Ket"], 
      SqrtBox[
       SubscriptBox["p", "\[Mu]"]]}]}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"a64942b9-63c0-4263-a0fe-6f35429d5e15"],
 " ."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->728131997,ExpressionUUID->"a005816e-4d8d-4d4a-8a0b-63765a2b3845"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Absorbing the probabilities into the vectors, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"], 
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
    "BraKet"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d0d92208-e7b6-46b8-a35a-0cfc6626e2f6"],
 " gives the probability to find the state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]", "\[Prime]"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fb97a909-19db-4a62-bc1d-e946a8091be0"],
 " in the ensemble. The corresponding density operator is constructed as"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1352652973,ExpressionUUID->"39c49edc-3429-4a4c-9393-68555d9db8d2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Rho]", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Sum]", "\[Mu]"], 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]", "\[Prime]"]},
       "Ket"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubsuperscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]", "\[Prime]"]},
       "Bra"]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "74a4cf65-6dcb-4af3-8b5b-2ee72c924331"],
 " ,"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->776630069,ExpressionUUID->"6baee369-ced2-4c6e-8039-16172faa458c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "and is certainly equivalent to the expression in terms of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Mu]"]},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b1cb5cd2-bed0-418b-b996-29f09619fb79"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->415963217,ExpressionUUID->"85966824-33ba-47e0-b0f5-75c7a4781227"],

